{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480243"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:39:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:39:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"31"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/31"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.06,0.25,0.41,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"31"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52033"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/31"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"31"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37348"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"867"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5689"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15018"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52033"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man presents with a nine month history of difficulty swallowing. This is associated with a sensation of choking and bringing back small particles of food and other other recently swallowed materials, such as tablets. He often wakes up at night, coughing. His medical history includes a cerebrovascular accident four years ago, motor neurone disease diagnosed three months ago, an appendicectomy at the age of 17, and childhood asthma. He does not have any other symptoms, has no allergies, is active around the house and looks after his wife in their own home. On examination his blood pressure is 136/92mmHg, pulse 90/min and temperature 37.2C. He is 174cm tall, weighs 82kgs, and is of pale complexion. Otherwise, the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Myasthenia gravis","Oesophageal cancer","Pseudobulbar palsy","Pharyngeal pouch","Achalasia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAll the conditions listed could be associated with swallowing issues, however, this clinical presentation is consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Epharyngeal pouch\u003C/strong\u003E (Zenker\u0027s diverticulum). The age of the patient, the duration of symptoms and the coughing back of particles of food and tablets fit well for this diagnosis. The nocturnal aspiration (waking up coughing) is also suggestive of some form of oesophageal obstruction. It is unlikely to be a \u003Cstrong\u003Emotility disorder\u003C/strong\u003E as there is no suggestion that the dysphagia was initially worse with fluids rather than solids. Large volume regurgitation is a prominent feature in \u003Cstrong\u003Eachalasia\u003C/strong\u003E and is not present here. The small volume, particulate matter of what the patient expectorates is very typical of a pharyngeal pouch, where small objects (typically tablets) become lodged in the pouch. They can them be dislodged when the patient coughs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe history is too long for it to be a \u003Cstrong\u003Emalignant\u003C/strong\u003E process. That he is capable of running a house and looking after his wife suggests that his \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevious stroke \u003C/strong\u003Eand the \u003Cstrong\u003Emotor neurone disease\u003C/strong\u003E have not left him with much physical incapacity and thus these two conditions are unlikely to be responsible for his swallowing problems.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dysphagia that is initially worse with fluids rather than solids suggests a possible motility disorder"],"references":["Law R, Katzka DA, Baron TH. Zenker\u0027s diverticulum. Clin Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2014; 12:1773-82. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24055983/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37348"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"31"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37348"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-02T09:42:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-02T09:42:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"31"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52033"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"hea